시점과 논리를 농락하는 짧은 퍼즐 게임

게임을 시작하자마자 컴퓨터로 빨려 들어가는 플레이어, 그리고 뇌를 녹이는 데 집중한 퍼즐을 풀어가면 되는 퍼즐 게임이다. 퍼즐의 종류는 단순 뇌지컬 보다는 퍼즐 플랫포머 형식의 퍼즐들인데, 애초에 주인공의 이동속도가 꽤 빠르고 점프력도 좋아서 가끔 퍼즐 플랫포머에서 보이는 “컨트롤이 거지같아서 못 해먹겠네” 라는 생각은 거의 들지 않았다. 퍼즐에 막힌 경우는 주변을 잘 둘러보지 못했다던가, 아니면 진짜로 퍼즐을 어떻게 풀어야 하는지 생각을 해야 하는 경우가 전부였다. (사실, 퍼즐들이 고난이도의 컨트롤이나 어려운 메커니즘을 활용하는 경우는 없어서 한 구간에 너무 오래 막힌 경우는 없었다.) 퍼즐들의 경우, Antichamber라는 게임의 초반부에 퍼즐을 풀면서 느낀 당황스러움과 재미가 생각날 정도로 시점의 전환이라는 컨셉을 잘 살린 것 같아서 마음에 들었다. 특히 게임 초반부부터 나오는 중력을 마음대로 변환할 수 있는 퍼즐들이나, 엔딩 직전에 나오는 행성 관련 퍼즐은 (이 경우 게임 내 힌트가 부족해서 결국 공략을 찾아보긴 했지만) 연출과 퍼즐 자체가 마음에 들었다. 한 가지 아쉬운 점은 플레이타임은 그렇게 길지 않다는 점인데, 애초에 게임 자체가 무료이기도 하고, 짧은 시간 안에 뇌를 적절히 자극하고 박수 칠 때 떠난 느낌이라 지나치게 아쉬운 느낌은 들지 않았다.


결론적으로, 스토리가 명확하게 있는 게임은 아니지만, 애초에 게임 내 포커스가 맞춰진 부분이 뇌를 녹이는 퍼즐 쪽에 맞춰져 있고 그 역할을 적절히 해낸 거 같아서 추천한다. 다만, 만약 나처럼 1인칭 게임을 하다가 멀미를 하는 사람이라면 게임 초반부에 약간 멀미가 올 수 있으니 주의를 하는 걸 권장한다.

Einfach mal um die Ecke denken, lieber Leser...
Eigentlich ganz leicht, oder?
Übrigens nicht zu verwechseln mit querdenken, das machen wir hier sowieso nicht.
Aber Du und ich, wir können hier beide mal ein bisschen über den Tellerrand schauen, haste Bock?
Ist eigentlich auch egal, nun hast Du schon angefangen zu lesen und bist eh schon mit im Boot, da wirst Du nur nass, wenn Du jetzt noch raus springst.
Also Tellerrand, aufgepasst!
Einen Teller gibts in diesem Game leider nicht und ja, bitte zügle Deine Enttäuschung... ABER wir schauen hier auch nur über den metaphorischen Tellerrand, toll oder?
Und Du merkst schon, das hier wird mal wieder so eine verzwickte und verzwackte Sache: ein Spiel, wo einem das Hirn wehtut und man nicht mit dem langsam rinnenden Sabberfaden am Mundwinkel stumpf vor sich hin zocken kann, sondern richtig Kopfarbeit verrichtet.
Juhu???

Du sagst es mal wieder, lieber Leser: JUHU!
Hier wird geknobelt, gepuzzelt und gegrübelt, dass die Schwarte kracht und das Hirnschmalz in Strömen fließt.
In diesem spiel gehts nämlich - wie so oft im wahren Leben ja auch - um die richtige Betrachtungsweise.
Perspektive heißt das Zauberwort und das zaubert uns auch sogleich nen Lächeln ins gerade noch stirnfaltige Gesicht.
So sind jetzt also Lachfalten angesagt, doch weniger lachhaft ist hier dann der Schwierigkeitsgrad.
Denn dieses Game ist kurz.
So richtig.
Kurz.
Etwa zehn Minütchen, dann biste durch und fragst Dich, welche zwei anderen Spiele Du nun in der Mittagspause noch zocken sollst...
...
... ODER...
...
... Du sitzt auch nach ner Stunde noch da, zermarterst Dir das Hirn, beißt in die Tischplatte, zermalmst Deine Maus mit stahlhartem Griff vor purer geistiger Anspannung krampfender Gamer-Hände...
... und dann gibst Du halt einfach auf.
Tja, wie son Weichei ;-)

Aber das stimmt natürlich nicht, schließlich bist Du ein knallharter Gamer-Alleskönner und beißt Dich gefälligst durch, aber hiermit bist Du eben gewarnt, leicht wirds nicht.
Dafür musst Du Dir den Kopf nicht über ne komplexe Story zerbrechen, die gibts nämlich einfach gar nicht.
Und falls doch, dann ist sie unter so vielen Metaebenen verborgen, das würde hier den Rahmen sprengen, Dir das alles haarklein zu erklären.
Musste schon selber drauf kommen.
Ich hab das natürlich alles im ersten Sekundenbruchteil durchblickt und verstanden, aber nur weil ich eben so überirdisch begabt bin und so...
... und Du bist eben...
... naja, Du halt ;-)

Quatsch! Story gibts wirklich nicht, ist aber auch nicht schlimm, denn hier gehts um geniale Puzzle Kost, die Du mittels verzwickter und verrückter Änderung Deines Blickwinkels oft erst im fünften Anlauf enträtseln kannst.
Das macht Spaß, motiviert und die häufigen "Aha-Momente" fühlen sich belohnend an und sind ne wirkungsvolle Karotte vor der Nase.
Beim Szenario fragst Du Dich vielleicht, wieso Dich immer Dutzende Grusel-Augen von überall her beobachten und was das alles mit Walen zu tun hat und mit dem Universum und...
...
... noch dazu mit...
... den Spoilern, die wir hier mal auslassen.
Darfst Du Dir alles schön selbst erknobeln.

Grafisch ists zweckmäßig gemacht und die vielen kleinen Momente, in denen sich durch die Veränderung der Perspektive ganze Räume verschieben oder Objekte zu gänzlich anderen werden oder sogar noch viel wildere, tiefgreifendere Metamorphosen stattfinden... die sind schon echte Augenöffner zum Teil.
Sound gibts fast gar nicht, passt aber zum Gesamtkonzept.

Stell Dich also auf eine kurze, oder je nach Puzzle-Können etwas längere abenteuerliche Reise ein, auf der Du die Dinge auch mal aus nem anderen Blickwinkel betrachten wirst und auch mal über den besagten Tellerrand, oder gar den Rand des eigenen geistigen Horizonts schauen wirst.
Und dabei, sowie beim Knobeln, Puzzeln, überaus nachdenklich Nachdenken und vor allem Staunen wünsch ich Dir wie immer...

... viel Spaß ;-)

Évaluation publiée le 19 mars 2023
Einmal gebratenes Gehirn auf Toast bitte

Kommt sofort!

Gameplay
“Frame of Mind” ist ein kurzes, aber sehr abstraktes Erkundungsspiel aus der Ego-Perspektive, in dem wir spielerisch die Dinge oft anders angehen lassen müssen. Da ist eine Wand? Dann dreh dich um geh rückwärts, denn dann ist sie nicht mehr da und weitere kleine Spielereien dieser Art, die mich ein wenig an Antichamber erinnern, wobei das Genannte nochmal deutlich krasser ist. Nach ca. 30 Minuten ist man mit dem Spiel dann auch schon durch.

Story
Eine wirkliche Geschichte hat das Spiel nicht. Vielleicht träumt unser Charakter in Wirklichkeit und erschafft sich eine surreale Traumwelt? Das würde zumindest erklären, warum wir in unserer eigenen Wohnung anfangen. Ein bisschen interpretierbar ist das Spiel auf jeden Fall.

Grafik/Sound
Der Grafikstil ist schon besonders und hat mit seinen klaren Kanten auch mit dem Gameplay zu tun. Denn ein Clue des Spiels ist ganz klar die Spielerei mit den Perspektiven, die sich ständig verändern und so neue Gänge und Räume offenbaren, wenn man genau hinschaut. Ziemlich clever! Der Soundtrack zum Spiel ist klein, aber passend und gut.

Fazit
„Frame of Mind“ ist eines dieser kostenlosen Spiele, mit denen man mal eine halbe Stunde füllen kann. Besonders macht den Titel seine Grafik und seine irrationale Art der Rätselstellung. „Frame of Mind“ ist gerade für Leute interessant, die auch Portal oder das angesprochene Antichamber gut finden. Ich habe das Spiel auch nur über die Empfehlung eines Steamfreundes mitbekommen, kann es mittlerweile aber auch selber klar empfehlen. Der Kreislauf wird also fortgesetzt!


Du stehst auf knifflige Rätselspiele? Dafür habe ich in meiner Steamgruppe sogar eine eigene Liste angefertigt, genau wie auch für kostenlose Spiele, die man sich mal anschauen kann. Wenn das noch nicht reicht, gibt es noch die German Steam Community, für die ich auch öfters schreibe. Schau mal dort vorbei!

La véritable réalité est toujours irréaliste. (Franz Kafka)

Courte expérience qui n'est pas sans rappeler des jeux comme Antichamber et qui dure entre quelques minutes pour les plus rapides à une petite heure pour ceux qui prennent davantage leur temps.

Il faut aimer observer, explorer et expérimenter pour réussir à avancer.

I tried Frame of Mind, okay. I really did. And honestly? The premise is neat and the execution is fantastic. I love the artstyle. Really, I do. The biggest problem here is that the game is incredibly high contrast and my eyes started to hurt after about five minutes. That, and the fact that every surface is white makes it difficult to remember where you are, and oftentimes you'll fall just by moving your mouse the wrong way (though that may be a feature, not a bug).

I think Frame of Mind has potential and I'm sure that people who can get through it will love it. But if you have any sort of eye troubles at all, or even if you don't, I highly suggest that you at least set a timer and take breaks if you really want to play this game. It will hurt. A lot.

I love this game.
Sure, it's no Portal, but it's a great puzzle game nonetheless.
My only real criticism is that it gave me a headache, but I'm willing to say that it's my own problem.
I would recommend this game to anyone looking for a mind-bending puzzle game.
Art style is incredible, 9/10
It always introduced the new mechanics gradually, and in a really clever way too. I never felt like there was something I didn't know, except for the solution, of course.
I just don't think it has a lot of replay value, but then again, that's the case with a lot of puzzle games, that once you know the solution, there's no reason to play that puzzle again. But this is just an issue with the puzzle format, not anything with the game itself.
I'm not really sure where I'm going with this, really. I can't recommend this game enough, unless you're easily disoriented, because yes, it's one of those games.
But even if you don't know what you're doing, it's a real fun play. The art style is just- *mwah*
Though one small criticism is the lack of direction. It was very often that I wasn't sure what the game was trying to teach me, and blindly stumbling around is actually a strategy that works for certain levels. I'm not sure why, but it doesn't break the game or anything, it's just a bit weird.
Overall, 9/10, great game, but nothing revolutionary or anything.

Évaluation publiée le 3 mai 2021
Frame of Mind

Un juego bastante corto lleno de ilusión optica continua ♥♥♥ trucos de percepción, que, por si no los analizas detenidamente, continúas haciendo lo mismo que el resto por sentido común..

Los controles son bastante basicos al igual que sus mecánicas, por lo que se entiende el hecho de ser gratuito.
En tema de niveles, son puros cuartos chicos que esconden otros desde otra perspectiva.

Origen
El origen del juego nos deja un mensaje sobre la locura que son las tareas cotidianas (que parecen apreciarse en la primera prueba de oficinas y el de varios recuadros del mismo que representa ''El Calendario''), que por si bien no las evadimos por muy lógico que sean, seguimos estando ''en la caja/circulo'' como bien nos detalla el sinopsis del titulo, una vez realizado tu primera prueba, bienvenido, has entrado al camino de lo ilógico, ♥♥♥ lo que te lleva a la siguiente etapa cotidiana y así que empiezas a darte cuenta que cada ''etapa'', desafía tu nivel de razonamiento moral/óptica, por lo que empiezas hacer 1 de 2; Rendirte y repetir lo mismo que el resto, o empezar a ver tu entorno de otra perspectiva y evadir la lógica de la situación para abrirte nuevo camino.

Un juego que sin lugar a duda, merece la pena probar (siendo gratuito de su estilo), o al menos para familiarizarte ♥♥♥ juegos como Portal y Superliminal. : )

Pues es cierto que es relajante, pues los niveles no te lastiman mucho la vista (aunque si desorientan demasiado), y el ambiente hace la experiencia bastante entretenida y comoda a medida que avanzas mientras te enfocas.
(curioso ya que el juego no tiene opción para configurar los ajustes visuales/sonoros, está bastante bien desarrollado)

Dato gracioso,
- hay otro control aparte de los 4 que te da la descripción.. ¿Cómo soluciono el puzzle?: ♥♥♥ el Cerebro.
- Que varios de los que reseñaron positivo como negativo diciendo que ''da dolor de cabeza'', sean ejemplos contrarios del propósito del juego. *Risa*
- Total de tiempo jugado: 69 minutos; ese numero me acosa en todas partes.

SPIRITOUSPOND a écrit :
PROS:
- Juego Psicológico.
- Niveles ópticos desafiantes que representan etapas cotidianas.
- Gratuito para familiarizarse en este tipo de puzzles.
- Bastante Entretenido.
- Ligero para equipos de bajo recurso.
- Ambiente agradable para los oidos.
- Speedrun para batir tiempo record.

CONTRAS:
- Que sea MUY CORTO y se te de por eliminarlo una vez terminado.

9/10

Me hubiese gustado que fuese más largo y ♥♥♥ más modos, pero siendo un proyecto indie escolar realizado por [Sample Text] Studios, y lo muy básico que este parezca en su estilo es respetable la razón de que sea accesible para todos. Y siendo un equipo de 6 personas, titulo ganador de un premio Actual.. Nos es de reconocer su gran potencial ♥♥♥ sus primeros 2 años de estudio.

Consejos buenos que alargarían su uso individual:
- Jugarlo ♥♥♥ amigos/familiares.
- Si eres maestro en psicología, éste puede servirle como practica de razonamiento visual para sus alumnos.
- Hacer Gameplay/Steaming del Titulo.
- jugarlo como pasatiempo en cualquier parte (portátil).

De otra manera, una vez terminado.. ahí muere.. Gracias.

I get that you're supposed to generally intuit your way into the game, understand how it works by looking at the environment and finding all the little ways the rules are different than how you'd expect. I don't recommend this for anybody who likes puzzles or people who are easily made motion sick.

Juego pequeño de puzzle en primera persona monocromático, mezcla ilusoria entre Antichamber y Manifold Garden. Cortito y al pie.

Se maneja ♥♥♥ la formula típica de ir resolviendo habitaciones, los puzzles estan buenos al igual que las mecánicas que presenta. Invito a que las explores por tu cuenta. El juego es GRATIS y liviano.

Los puzzles están bien diseñados y la estética en general está bien lograda. No hay mucho mas para decir.

+No perdes nada hermano, es gratis.
+Interesante el uso de la monocromía.
+Si buscas juegos completos ♥♥♥ esta misma onda tenés los que nombre arriba. Son lo más. Tenes el The Bridge también si te va toda la geometría Escheriana.

Évaluation publiée le 12 mai 2021
Sigue a "La Cruceta Inquieta", mentor de Steam
A medio camino de un "walking simulator" y un juego de rompecabezas, "Frame of Mind" no hace bien ni una cosa ni la otra. Aparte de un estilo artístico sensiblemente minimalista y que, como ocurrió en mi caso, funciona como principal reclamo, el título que nos ocupa no ofrece mucho más que una sucesión de estancias por las que avanzar mediante un sistema de algo parecido a rompecabezas que ni resulta del todo lógico, ni mucho menos resulta satisfactorio. Por supuesto, aunque uno termina por encontrarle cierta lógica y algo de coherencia, en ningún momento alcanzan el nivel suficiente como para hacernos sentir que el esfuerzo puesto en su resolución merece la pena; convirtiéndose todo el proceso en un tortuoso paseo al que cuanto antes querremos poner fin. Todo esto principalmente, aunque no siempre, se debe a la utilización del propio apartado artístico como vehículo para la resolución de unos puzles que utilizan los juegos cromáticos o de perspectiva que el aspecto gráfico bicolor aporta a la jugabilidad, convirtiendo a veces puzles de dificulta irrisoria en un suplicio porque no seamos capaces de distinguir que a la vuelta de la esquina hay un pasillo que, en un principio, parece un muro infranqueable.

"Frame of Mind" transforma su prometedor estilo gráfico y artístico en una sucesión de puzles que, por no decir que es aburrida y hasta desesperante, sí resulta tener una lógica cogida ♥♥♥ pinzas y carente de toda capacidad de recompensa para el jugador.

В игре вы решаете несложные головоломки, которые в большинстве случаев решаются хождением по стенам. Да, здесь вы можете перемещаться в разных плоскостях и пространствах, что делает геймплей очень необычным и моментами ломает мозг.

Отличная бесплатная игра для тех, кто хочет по новому взглянуть на головоломки.

Évaluation publiée le 8 octobre 2023
The game is short (finished it in less than 30 minutes), but it is free and has a cool vibe of its own. The gameplay relies on understanding what simple mechanics are available at a certain time and finding your way through a labyrinth. Some of the challenge comes from an interesting play with portals, perspective and simple puzzles, while some of it comes simply from making sense of the hard to read, monochromatic visuals. On that matter, there were a few times, when even though I did manage to progress, I wasn't too sure what had just physically unfold in front of me.

Controls (moving and jumping mainly) are a bit too brisk, to a point where I quickly got motion sickness (and I don't figure myself usually sensitive to it). The progression is usually fine, only rarely cut short by less entertaining elements (one specifically annoying to find button in the middle of an otherwise nice little puzzle comes to mind). The whole thing is quite abstract, so don't expend much of a story.

I see no reason not to recommend. It's free, takes no time to complete, and remains a strong example of a still relatively rarely explored kind of walking simulator.
7/10

Definitely worth your time if you enjoy games with unique visual styles, puzzles based on optical illusions (or things similar to that), and artworks using streams-of-consciousness to describe the human experience. The art is clean but the environment and the puzzles are surreal, something that I enjoy a lot. Puzzles are not super hard: I would like the game more if it's more difficult, but it is fine and enjoyable as it is. The game is short (about two hours for me), which is something I appreciate--brought me an unforgettable, complete experience in a less amount of time than some longer games do. I would be happy to pay a few dollars for it.

Mind Bending ♥♥♥♥.
Definitely worth playing as it is free and quite short (under 1 hr)
Most puzzles are very cool, music adds to the atmosphere well, graphics are very nice.

Despite this, I do have some criticisms. Some puzzles were very unclear with what to do, and i ended up doing random things till i solved them, especially later ones.
Despite it just being ambient soundscapes with minimal melodic elements, the music did get a bit repetitive by the end of the game, would like to see some variations.
No story or explanation on what any of the environments meant, throughout the game i liked this, thinking of theories and reasons behind the elements used, hoping they would be explained in some form at the end of the game, but alas, it was not.
Speaking of the end of the game, it is very disappointing, and i didn't realise i had finished the game, it just.. kicks you back to the title screen, now with a 'speedrun' option on the menu.
I know this review has been quite negative, but a lot of these criticisms are less of an issue for me since it was a free game, i would be a bit disappointed if i paid for it though.
All up, if your bored one afternoon, play this game, free, short and some very fun puzzles.

Frame of Mind is a surreal puzzle exploration game that uses optical illusions, shifts in perspective, and other visual tricks as its gimmick. It has a highly stylized monochromatic presentation that reminds me of a visual novel for some reason.
Storywise it's very bare bones. There is surrealist symbolism going on that you can dissect, but there isn't much else going on. Its strengths are the mind-bending puzzles and style anyways.
I'm not sure if it's fun though. I often felt that I was just stumbling through the world and bumping into the solutions without thinking. I guess I recommend it since its free and you can make up your own mind. It's certainly not a waste of time.

Évaluation publiée le 14 aout 2022
This game represents all obtuse, mind bending and mind breaking puzzles to ever exist.
Granted, I did complete this game in under an hour, it still left my brain with psychological scars from which I may never recover.

On a more serious note, this game is a really good demonstration of the developers prowess; the opening level of the game works wonders on the player's mind to shake off the convention of puzzle games. Having something so unexpected at the start throws the player off of rational thought- so you begin to wonder, "How do I twist the puzzle world to my advantage?" And from then on, the game becomes very interesting and addictive.

The simple colour scheme of blue and white ensures the use of 'Perspective Awareness', where the player tries to comprehend the actual scale of the puzzle.
The gravity defying puzzles that occur after the initial 4 puzzles are some of the best this game has to offer.

Overall, this can be a great full length puzzle and philosophical game like The Talos Principle or Antichamber.
10/10

It's an interesting puzzle game playing with perspective, gravity and dimensions, with a minimalist art style that's impossible to dislike and visual humor that needs no words to be entertaining (hard not to chuckle at a printer printing pancakes). That said, you often feel like you're staring at a black or white screen, especially in the biggest roiom, where the art style gets in the way, preventing you from seeing where wall boundaries and doorways are.

As a result some puzzles will end up being resolved without even know how, in fact I can think of at least three rooms I have solved just by staring at a ceiling in a random spot and I have no clue what happened. One time I stood in front of a toilet stall hinted at by a reflection, trying to figure out what to do with it, looked up and I was at the next level, and I couldn't tell you why.

Worth a try but I can see many giving up on it.

Évaluation publiée le 21 mars 2021
Late to the party, empty handed
Everything Frame of Mind does, we saw elsewhere. The "non-eucleidean" space, the specific puzzle mechanisms, the "we live in a modernist society" kinda critique, all of these were already covered by games like The Stanley Parable or Antichamber. The first problem is, these concepts were, let's say, revolutionary when these came out (2011 ad 2013 respectively), so when a game is built solely on these things nowadays, it really is somewhat lacking. This is even amplified by the second problem, that whereas in Antichamber the rules of the game were clear-cut by repeating consistent elements (and in The Stanley Parable the rules were self-evident), Frame of Mind simply doesn't tell the player the rules at all, neither explicitly (through an explanation), nor implicitly (through the valve-esque model of training, repeating and a "field test" - see HL2E1 dev. commentary for more). So in practice, you're stuck in what appears to be a puzzle, but you don't even know what the goal is, which logically prevents you from solving said puzzle. Despite these faults, the game is, after all, free, which means that it doesn't need to adhere to the same standards a commercial product would.
So the bottom line is, as a little gameplay experiment, yeah, okay, but if it gets developed into something bigger, then it needs to be developed heavily.

Короткая. Бесплатная. В духе игры Antichamber. Загадки не сложные, но немного шевелить мозгами заставляет, что уже плюс. Музыка миленькая и не успевает надоедать, т.к. геймплея на ~40 минут. + минут 15 можно потратить просто на то, чтобы любоваться деталями уровней.

Минус игры в том, что она сходу не поясняет, что она и во что нас погружает, поэтому можно с первых секунд затупить, разозлиться и выйти, скоропостижно забыв о ее существовании. Единственное управление игры: мышь и WASD, ВЗАИМОДЕЙСТВИЕ с предметами происходит автоматически при приближении к предмету.

8/10

Évaluation publiée le 31 janvier 2021
It's not all that often that a game like this comes along. We had Antichmber, Beyond Perception, End of File: Prototype, Non Euclidean Room, Fragments of Euclid, Manifold Garden, Superliminal and now Frame of Mind. A rather short list spanning a decade. Yes, games like this are truly rare and should be enjoyed whenever found.

That being said, this is short, really short. You will still find it charming and fascinating, but this is short enought that the free price seems unfortunately apropiate. Here's hoping the developers next game will have a bit more meat on it, people need to eat and work of this calibre should really be remunerated.

Also, played this on Linux via Proton. Minor graphical glitches and a frame rate that stayed over 300fps from most of the game but dropped at around 90 once or twice. There were also a few frame tearing issues. Since most reading this will be playing this on Windows, here's hoping you won't have any such issues.

Évaluation publiée le 28 janvier 2021
Produit reçu gratuitement

Yet another situation where this is more of an artistic experience than a game, but make no mistake. By any definition, this is in fact a game.

For starters, this is gorgeous, it masterfully uses negative space, along with stunningly nice minimalist visual with lighting effects that completely mess with your sense of perspective. That is where the game part comes in, figuring out the worlds rules to solve puzzles to progress is the name of the game.

I admit I got to what I'll call the kitchen, and did get stuck, I looked up a hint, progressed several more rooms, and am currently stuck, but I feel like I'm getting close to getting it without looking. There were points where even though I'm on mouse and keyboard, I almost felt like I was in VR (I've not had a ton of time on VR to be fair). I could imagine some of the optical tricks and shifts in perspective could be unsettling for some, may give a few motion sickness.

But it's really hard to understate just how impressed I was. There are points where the world almost starts to make sense, but then it really doesn't again shortly after. It's free, it's beautiful, it makes you think a little bit. It's an enriching artistic experience. I do not think I can give this game enough praise. When the developer decides to put together something they want paid for, that will at least be worth watching for.
